            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-b60bd1 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-d86123 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-6b4cd0\"><h2>Contents</h2></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000016": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000016",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-b60bd1 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-d86123 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-6b4cd0\"><table>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000021\">INTRODUCTION</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000028\">YOUTH Æt. 1-25—1469-94</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000035\">OFFICE Æt. 25-43—1494-1512</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000054\">LITERATURE AND DEATH Æt. 43-58—1512-27</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000075\">THE MAN AND HIS WORKS</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000100\">DEDICATION</$link><br>\n<br></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"c6 pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000115\">THE PRINCE</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000118\">CHAPTER I. HOW MANY KINDS OF PRINCIPALITIES THERE ARE, AND BY WHAT MEANS THEY ARE ACQUIRED</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000129\">CHAPTER II. CONCERNING HEREDITARY PRINCIPALITIES</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000138\">CHAPTER III. CONCERNING MIXED PRINCIPALITIES</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000189\">CHAPTER IV. WHY THE KINGDOM OF DARIUS, CONQUERED BY ALEXANDER, DID NOT REBEL AGAINST THE SUCCESSORS OF ALEXANDER AT HIS DEATH</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000206\">CHAPTER V. CONCERNING THE WAY TO GOVERN CITIES OR PRINCIPALITIES WHICH LIVED UNDER THEIR OWN LAWS BEFORE THEY WERE ANNEXED</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000215\">CHAPTER VI. CONCERNING NEW PRINCIPALITIES WHICH ARE ACQUIRED BY ONE’S OWN ARMS AND ABILITY</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000236\">CHAPTER VII. CONCERNING NEW PRINCIPALITIES WHICH ARE ACQUIRED EITHER BY THE ARMS OF OTHERS OR BY GOOD FORTUNE</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000277\">CHAPTER VIII. CONCERNING THOSE WHO HAVE OBTAINED A PRINCIPALITY BY WICKEDNESS</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000300\">CHAPTER IX. CONCERNING A CIVIL PRINCIPALITY</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000321\">CHAPTER X. CONCERNING THE WAY IN WHICH THE STRENGTH OF ALL PRINCIPALITIES OUGHT TO BE MEASURED</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000332\">CHAPTER XI. CONCERNING ECCLESIASTICAL PRINCIPALITIES</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000349\">CHAPTER XII. HOW MANY KINDS OF SOLDIERY THERE ARE AND CONCERNING MERCENARIES</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000386\">CHAPTER XIII. CONCERNING AUXILIARIES, MIXED SOLDIERY, AND ONE’S OWN</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000421\">CHAPTER XIV. THAT WHICH CONCERNS A PRINCE ON THE SUBJECT OF WAR</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000434\">CHAPTER XV. CONCERNING THINGS FOR WHICH MEN, AND ESPECIALLY PRINCES, ARE PRAISED OR BLAMED</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000441\">CHAPTER XVI. CONCERNING LIBERALITY AND MEANNESS</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000454\">CHAPTER XVII. CONCERNING CRUELTY AND CLEMENCY, AND WHETHER IT IS BETTER TO BE LOVED THAN FEARED</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000477\">CHAPTER XVIII. CONCERNING THE WAY IN WHICH PRINCES SHOULD KEEP FAITH</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000504\">CHAPTER XIX. THAT ONE SHOULD AVOID BEING DESPISED AND HATED</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000555\">CHAPTER XX. ARE FORTRESSES, AND MANY OTHER THINGS TO WHICH PRINCES OFTEN RESORT, ADVANTAGEOUS OR HURTFUL?</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000572\">CHAPTER XXI. HOW A PRINCE SHOULD CONDUCT HIMSELF SO AS TO GAIN RENOWN</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000593\">CHAPTER XXII. CONCERNING THE SECRETARIES OF PRINCES</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000604\">CHAPTER XXIII. HOW FLATTERERS SHOULD BE AVOIDED</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000621\">CHAPTER XXIV. WHY THE PRINCES OF ITALY HAVE LOST THEIR STATES</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000632\">CHAPTER XXV. WHAT FORTUNE CAN EFFECT IN HUMAN AFFAIRS AND HOW TO WITHSTAND HER</$link></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000653\">CHAPTER XXVI. AN EXHORTATION TO LIBERATE ITALY FROM THE BARBARIANS</$link><br>\n<br></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"c6 pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000682\">DESCRIPTION OF THE METHODS ADOPTED BY THE DUKE VALENTINO WHEN MURDERING VITELLOZZO VITELLI, OLIVEROTTO DA FERMO, THE SIGNOR PAGOLO, AND THE DUKE DI GRAVINA ORSINI</$link><br>\n<br></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><$link class=\"c6 pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000723\">THE LIFE OF CASTRUCCIO CASTRACANI OF LUCCA</$link></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000017": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000017",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-b60bd1 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-d86123 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000018": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000018",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-b60bd1 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-d86123 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\"><p class=\"letter\"><i>Nicolo Machiavelli, born at Florence on 3rd May 1469. From 1494 to 1512 held an official post at Florence which included diplomatic missions to various European courts. Imprisoned in Florence, 1512; later exiled and returned to San Casciano. Died at Florence on 22nd June 1527.</i></p></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000019": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000019",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-b60bd1 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-d86123 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000020": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000020",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-b60bd1 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-d86123 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000021": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000021",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-b60bd1 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-d86123 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\"><h2><a></a>INTRODUCTION</h2></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000022": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000022",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-b60bd1 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-d86123 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000023": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000023",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-b60bd1 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-d86123 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\"><p>Nicolo Machiavelli was born at Florence on 3rd May 1469. He was the second son of Bernardo di Nicolo Machiavelli, a lawyer of some repute, and of Bartolommea di Stefano Nelli, his wife. Both parents were members of the old Florentine nobility.</p></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000024": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000024",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-b60bd1 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-d86123 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000025": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ac6d9189e2f126ac/text/000000025",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-b60bd1 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-d86123 twpub-ac6d9189e2f126ac-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\"><p>His life falls naturally into three periods, each of which singularly enough constitutes a distinct and important era in the history of Florence. His youth was concurrent with the greatness of Florence as an Italian power under the guidance of Lorenzo de’ Medici, Il Magnifico. The downfall of the Medici in Florence occurred in 1494, in which year Machiavelli entered the public service. During his official career Florence was free under the government of a Republic, which lasted until 1512, when the Medici returned to power, and Machiavelli lost his office. The Medici again ruled Florence from 1512 until 1527, when they were once more driven out. This was the period of Machiavelli’s literary activity and increasing influence; but he died, within a few weeks of the expulsion of the Medici, on 22nd June 1527, in his fifty-eighth year, without having regained office.</p></div></div>"
        },
